></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>(This equalizer exists because as an example of a connected limit, it is created/reflected by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span>, as Niu and Spivak remark.) I don't know how satisfying explicit this is for your purposes, but it's the formal dual of the construction recounted as Theorem 2.2 <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/colimits+in+categories+of+algebras#reflexive_coequalizers_and_cocompleteness\">here</a>.</p>",
